    <P>
      Ajax Health is an Outpatient provider of Population Health Management services. This means we are a healthcare facility, not a practitioner. As such, our job is to provide the infrastructure and oversight necessary to conduct population health management.
      Various practitioners will use our facility and the resources we provide to proactively manage the health of their patients.
    </P>
    <p>
      The primary method for effecting population health is this very web application. We are creating an entirely new type of practice management systems to help healthcare providers do the job we want them to do, rather than the job they are doing now.
      Our system is based on the principle that important health factors can be measured, either quantitatively or qualitatively, and by tracking changes in these important health measures over time we can proactively manage health.
    </p>
    <p>
      Most practice management systems are aimed at helping providers manage the process we discussed in the problem section. Things like scheduling appointments, capturing patient insurance information, archiving medical records, coding procedures, submitting claims, regulatory reporting and so on.
      Ajax Health is aimed at identifying patients with deteriorating health as indicated by the health measures our staff are taking. By taking regular measurements we are going to avoid waiting for the problem to surface before we start to treat the patient. If we have an older patient who is gaining weight rapidly,
       we know for a fact that they are headed for health problems down the road. Clinical research has already proven the link between being overweight and having worse health. So our goal is to make a tool which will allow us to identify the high risk patients before risk become reality.
    </p>
    <p>
        Why are people not already doing this? Well because they are too busy doing that! A typical doctor's office spends all day treating the patients in their waiting room. Our staff will spend all day looking for patients with deteriorating health. Well, likely the patient already knows they have deteriorating health,
        how are we going to get a patient to do something different in the face of no new information? Enter Wellness programs. The Affordable Care Act had many provisions attached to it. A rarely noticed one was the massive expansion in what is allowed to be called a wellness program.
        Wellness programs are of two types, one that pays everyone who satisfies a condition (participatory wellness programs) and one that rewards people for changes in health (health contingent wellness program). An example of a participatory wellness program is one where every member of an insurance plan who maintains a gym membership will get 100$ a year towards the cost of their gym membership.
        The other type of wellness program, and the one most impacted by the ACA, are health-contingent wellness programs. These types of programs reward patients who make certain changes in their health. For example people who reduce their blood sugar by 10% in a given quarter get rebate for their health insurance company.
    </p>
    <p>
        The healthcare industry has a well-defined stick: ever increasing cost. However until now there was no clear carrot. But now that we have more robust wellness program parameters, we can craft carrots to target various high risk groups. We know we spend a lot of money on treating diabetes. Why not pay the patient some money to proactively manage
        their diabetes and prevent becoming diabetic in the first place?
    </p>
    <p>
        Healthcare is a three legged stool. To make an impact you must provide value to each of the three legs. Read on as we discuss the main objectives and plans to realize our goals in the subsequent sections.
    </p>
