    <p>
      Patients are the drivers of the healthcare system. But I doubt most patients would feel that way. Usually you wait for something to go wrong and then a doctor tells them what to do. But there has to be a better way...
    </p>
    <p>
      We will offer several services to patients to try and change how the system operates. The first is tracking services and the second is Wellness programs. The first tells you where you need to improve, the second gives you a monetary reward for doing do.
    </p>
    <p>
      Before you can improve your health, you need to know how you are unhealthy. Unless you have had a specific reason to measure various aspects of your health, you likely have not. You may know how much you weigh and how that has changed over time. But how about you potassium levels? What about your hydration, blood glucose levels, or any other important health measure?
      Rather than waiting for you to have a problem because your body is out of whack, we can track these levels over time and give insight into how an individualâ€™s health is changing. At Ajax we get the benefit of data and a patient gets the benefit of knowledge. In the end it is the responsibility of the patient to live a healthy life. Doctors can, to various extents, help you when you break, but why break in the first place?
    </p>
    <p>
      We know that poorer health leads to higher healthcare costs. We may not know when those costs will occur but in the end, unhealthy people cost more money than healthier people. Since patients are in charge of their health, it is imperative that we get patients the tools to proactively manage their own health. But just knowing that you are unhealthy
      does not make you healthier, you need to change your behavior. This has historically been the major challenge of the healthcare industry. The Affordable Care Act expanded the scope of wellness programs specifically to give insurance companies shaper knives in the quest to cut healthcare costs.
      For patients this means that it is easier for health insurance companies to pay you to get healthier. Keeping track of who is getting healthier is not something that insurance companies are good at though, and that is a service that Ajax Health can provide. By tracking the change in health measures over time, we will have exactly the kind of data payers need to evaluate who should be paid under a health contingent wellness program.
      This means we can help patients get paid to make better decisions and to proactively manage their health.
    </p>
    
